WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.240
In this video, we're going to go through the process of pinning a dataset to Posit Connect

00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:09.480
using the pins package.

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:13.360
So over here on the left hand side, we have a pins demo R script, and we're going to walk

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:15.280
through all these steps.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:20.080
The first thing we'll do is install the pins package and then load the pins package into

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:21.200
our environment.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:27.280
So I'll highlight these lines of code and I'll hit run.

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:32.040
Now in order to use pins, you first have to define a board.

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:35.840
And so for this workflow, we're going to use Posit Connect as our board.

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:39.720
The first thing we need to do is register our board.

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:45.759
So the easiest way to do that is to go to tools, global options and select publishing.

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:48.560
So the top of my screen, I'll go to tools.

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:51.080
All the way at the bottom, we have global options.

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:54.279
And towards the bottom, we have publishing.

00:00:54.279 --> 00:00:58.040
Unfortunately, I do not have any Posit Connect instances registered.

00:00:58.040 --> 00:00:59.880
So we're going to connect to a new one.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:03.279
So I'll click connect here in the top right.

00:01:03.279 --> 00:01:06.199
We're going to choose Posit Connect.

00:01:06.199 --> 00:01:10.760
And here is where you want to provide the URL of your Connect instance.

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:13.800
I'll select next.

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:17.720
And we get this pop up menu to connect to R. That all looks good.

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:18.720
We'll hit connect.

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:25.199
I can close out of this and then connect account.

00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:29.120
All right, so we're now connected to our instance of Posit Connect.

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:33.480
I can apply these changes and hit OK.

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:36.919
All right, so now that we've registered our Posit Connect instance,

00:01:36.919 --> 00:01:41.160
we first need to define this Connect instance as our board.

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:46.000
And to do that, we're going to use the board connect function from the pins package.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.040
And we're going to call this my board.

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:50.000
So let me run this line of code.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.919
And you can see at the bottom, connecting to Posit Connect.

00:01:55.919 --> 00:01:59.480
And there's the URL for my Connect instance.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:02.879
And now we can actually pin the data set.

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:07.680
So in this example, we're going to use the pin write function from the pins package.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:11.440
And we're going to pin the mtcars data set.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:15.919
We're going to pin it to my Connect instance, which we registered in the previous step.

00:02:15.919 --> 00:02:17.960
We're going to call it mtcars data set.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:19.800
You can call it whatever you want.

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:23.199
And we're going to save this pin as a CSV file.

00:02:23.199 --> 00:02:24.520
So let's highlight all this.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:25.199
We'll hit Run.

00:02:29.039 --> 00:02:32.520
At the bottom of the screen, you can see writing to pin Ryan.

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:35.279
That's me, mtcars data set.

00:02:35.279 --> 00:02:38.360
And now we can actually switch over to Posit Connect.

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:41.720
And I can show you what a pinned data set looks like.

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:44.880
So here's the pinned data set, the mtcars data set.

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.600
You can actually get a snippet of what the data set looks like right here.

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:51.559
And you can actually scroll across.

00:02:51.559 --> 00:02:55.360
But most importantly, with pins, you want to know how to pull this pin

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:59.559
into your own workflow, into your own script, whatever you're developing.

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:02.559
And it provides the code on how to do that.

00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:03.600
So we're going to take this code.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:07.720
We're going to come back to Posit Workbench, the RStudio IDE within Posit Workbench

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:08.479
here.

00:03:08.479 --> 00:03:11.559
And we're going to read in that pin data set.

00:03:11.559 --> 00:03:14.880
So we'll use the pin read function from the pins package.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:18.399
We're going to, again, let pins know that this is the board I want to use.

00:03:18.399 --> 00:03:20.679
And I'm going to pull in this pin.

00:03:20.679 --> 00:03:23.360
That's my name, the mtcars data set.

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:24.279
So let's run that.

00:03:29.279 --> 00:03:35.240
And then you'll see here in my console, here is the printed out pinned mtcars

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:36.520
data set.

00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:40.600
And that is how you pin a data set to Posit Connect.

